HEADWORD: Brewis
<hw>Brew"is</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>brewis</ets>, <ets>brouwys</ets>, <ets>browesse</ets>,
<ets>brewet</ets>, OF. <ets>brouet</ets>, <ets>-s</ets> being the OF.
ending of the nom. sing. and acc. pl.; dim. of OHG. <ets>brod</ets>.
⟦root⟧93. See <er>Broth</er>, and cf. <er>Brose</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Broth or pottage.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let them of their Bonner's ⟦ldquo⟧beef⟦rdquo⟧ and
⟦ldquo⟧broth⟦rdquo⟧ make what <qex>brewis</qex> they please for their
credulous guests.</q> <rj><qau>Bp. Hall.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Bread soaked in broth, drippings of roast meat,
milk, or water and butter.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Brewsterite</ent>⟦br⟧
